00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,000
In the 1920s, radio radically transformed the way music was heard in Spain.

2
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:16,000
For the first time, symphonic concerts, operas and live performances reached homes without the need to go to theaters or concert halls.

3
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:22,000
This new sound experience marked a new mode of listening based on imagination and distance,

4
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:34,000
which anticipates features of contemporary digital culture, such as more democratic access to culture, ubiquitous listening, or the clear separation between those who produce sound and those who receive it.

5
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:44,000
The magazine Ondas, published in Madrid between 1925 and 1935 as the organ of UniÃ³n Radio, played a key role in this process.

6
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:57,000
Through photographs, illustrations, diagrams or evocative covers, the publication helped the public to see music and mentally construct sound worlds they could no longer physically witness.

7
00:00:57,000 --> 00:01:10,000
With more than 2,100 images, Ondas constituted an exceptional source in the field of musical iconography of the period, unparalleled in Spain at the time for the richness and variety of its visual material.

8
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:27,000
The virtual exhibition "Listening Without Seeing" invites you to explore this newspaper heritage from a rigorous perspective, expanding access to historical materials and promoting their dissemination beyond major cultural centers.

